<s> This is invalid; all the &amp;'s should be replaced with &amp;amp;  </s>
<s> No, the &amp;'s are delimiting the arguments of a GET-style CGI query.  </s>
<s> However, the &amp; before lookup is unnecessary, and may be confusing things.  </s>
<s> They *should* be &amp;amp;, although the one before lookup is also wrong.  </s>
<s> These &amp;s occur in a CDATA parameter context.  </s>
<s> In such a context, SGML entitities are replaced.  </s>
<s> That means that any paramter name that spoofs a known entity will get substituted by that entity and any that doesn't will be at the mercy of the parser's error recovery.  </s>
<s> The HTML 4 specification goes as far as to advise people creating form handlers to accept ; as a synonym for &amp; when the server is likely to be used with GET type form URLs coded in anchors rather than generated by forms.  </s>
<s> It does this to avoid the need to use &amp;amp;  </s>
